  "author_association": "MEMBER",
  "body": "(This is a potential security issue but exploiting is very difficult and may be impossible so just opening issue).\r\n\r\n```\r\nHi,\r\n\r\nwhile looking at Envoy's code, I noticed that in header_map_impl.cc's HeaderString::append and setCopy the calculation of the capacity of the buffer is:\r\n\r\n      uint32_t new_capacity = (string_length_ + size) * 2;\r\n      buffer_.dynamic_ = static_cast<char*>(malloc(new_capacity));\r\n      memcpy(buffer_.dynamic_, inline_buffer_, string_length_);\r\n\r\nsize is the parameter to the function and of type uint32_t. It is the size of the header value that gets copied into HeaderString.\r\n\r\nIf size is more than 2GB, the calculation of new_capacity can wrap and the allocation will be too small. Subsequently, an out-of-bounds heap write will occur during the memcpy.\r\n\r\nI also recommend to check if malloc returns !NULL to prevent null pointer dereference under memory pressure.\r\n\r\nTransferring 2GB could be a tough attack scenario but with HTTP2 compression it might be easier. I didn't invest time to do a proof-of-concept. Let me know if you need further information.\r\n\r\nIf you want to attribute the vulnerability please attribute to Felix Groebert, Google Security Team.\r\n\r\nThank you\r\nFelix\r\n```\r\n\r\nIn HTTP/1 hitting an overflow is definitely impossible due to max header block size tracking in http_parser.\r\n\r\nFor HTTP/2, we should add additional checking here: https://github.com/lyft/envoy/blob/master/source/common/http/http2/codec_impl.cc#L680 to make sure an individual header does not go above max size.\r\n\r\nIn the header map code itself we should probably add comments and debug asserts to check against overflow. If we want to be paranoid we can add RELEASE_ASSERT there but not a big fan of that if we think it is impossible.\r\n\r\nAssigning over to @alyssawilk for investigation/fix.",
